Piles: Causes, Symptoms, Treatment, and Prevention
Piles, also known as hemorrhoids, are swollen veins in the rectum and anus that cause discomfort, bleeding, and irritation. A common condition affecting millions globally, piles can significantly impact an individual's quality of life if left untreated. Understanding its causes, symptoms, and treatment options is crucial for effective management.

What are Piles?
Piles occur when the blood vessels in the anal area swell due to increased pressure. They can be classified into two types:
Internal Hemorrhoids: Located inside the rectum and typically painless, these may bleed during bowel movements.
External Hemorrhoids: Found under the skin around the anus, these are often painful and may itch or bleed.

Causes of Piles
Several factors contribute to the development of piles, including:
Chronic constipation: Straining during bowel movements increases pressure on rectal veins.
Sedentary lifestyle: Prolonged sitting or lack of exercise can contribute to poor blood circulation.
Pregnancy: Increased pressure on pelvic blood vessels during pregnancy may lead to piles.
Obesity: Excess weight exerts additional pressure on the lower rectum.
Dietary factors: A low-fiber diet can cause hard stools and straining.

Symptoms of Piles
The symptoms of piles vary depending on their type and severity. Common signs include:
Bright red blood after a bowel movement.
Pain or discomfort in the anal area.
Swelling or a lump near the anus.
Itching or irritation around the anus.
Mucus discharge during bowel movements.
